Use **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` — no real port, no real server process.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

### Example test class

```csharp
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using Xunit;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsList_ReturnsRegisteredTools()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/list",
            @params = new { }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var tools = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools");
        Assert.True(tools.GetArrayLength() > 0);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No real port** | `WebApplicationFactory` uses an in-memory `TestServer` — all HTTP stays in-process |
| **Full pipeline** | Middleware, routing, DI, auth — everything runs as in production |
| **MCP endpoint** | Adjust `"/mcp"` to match your actual route (e.g., `"/sse"`, `"/"`) |
| **Stateful sessions** | If your server uses SSE + session IDs, grab the session ID from the `initialize` response and pass it in subsequent requests via header or query string |
| **Mock dependencies** | Override services in the factory's `WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in fakes |

### If you need SSE streaming

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task Sse_StreamsMessages()
{
    var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Get, "/sse");
    var response = await _client.SendAsync(
        request, HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

    using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

    var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync();
    Assert.StartsWith("event:", line);
}
```

This gives you true end-to-end MCP protocol coverage with the speed of a unit test.
